On a local nature trail, we found a trunk of a dead tree in a small clump of western hemlock trees. A section of bark had been sliced away, exposing a dark orange inner layer. We found a living tree fallen beside it and concluded that it had torn away the bark. The living tree had some of this orange bark exposed at the roots, so we are wondering whether this shows a fungal disease. Photos show: detail of a piece of the separated bark (is that larvae in there?), the edge of the bark still on the tree, and an overview of the area where the bark was removed. We went back looking for any trace of a fruiting body and also to try to see whether this is redness is caused by exposure of bark to air.

I'm finally gaining a little confidence in ID'ing these Polypodium, or at least the ones that fit clearly at the ends of the spectrum. All 3 species are common along this trail, and often grow side by side. This plant looks somewhat close to glycyrrhiza in overall form, as it is rather soft & delicate, and has slightly pointed leaflets. The lack of hairs along the upper stem are sufficient to rule this species out however, and the long and narrow proportions, as well as the colour are a little different. It is far from the amorphum end of the scale, which would have much stiffer leaflets with fully round tips. Closeup photos confirm the lack of curled hairs (not to be confused with some debris that is present), and the narrow hydathodes. No sporangiasters were found either. Just one generation of leaves present (with only one persistent dead leaf hiding in the shelter behind). Note that the sori on this plant are not yet mature, indicating perhaps a later growth than typical.
With P. hesperium/amorphum at the top in the first photo. All three species of Polypodium common in the area.

Two plants in the first photo, both confirmed to have numerous sporangiasters in all the sori. All 3 species of Polypodium common in the area. These ones with thick fleshy leaves. The most noticeable feature of this species seems to be the curl to the leaves, which makes them difficult to lay flat to press. Particular the lower leaflets are highly folded in towards the center, so have to be carefully spread. This characteristic is then lost of course in flat preserved specimens. The leaves also tend to grow out in all directions (often horizontal), whereas hesperium on average tends to have the leaves more uniformly drooping downward (per its glycyrrhiza heritage). The sporangiasters show as small black dots in the closeup photos, and are very plentiful. The last two photos are of a frond from the lower plant, while the others are from the upper plant. The hydathodes are much less conspicuous than they are on hesperium, likely due to the thicker/fleshier leaf. They often do not show up from the underside at all, and are seen best from the upperside. On the hesperium sample I looked at (https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/100205216), they could be viewed from either side, and the connecting veins were also much more visible. At this time of year it is difficult to gauge the ages of the leaves, as the sori are mature on both this years and last years leaves. I will add photos of other plants that better highlight this trait.

Just a couple of fronds, growing with P. hesperium. The last photo shows the 4 fronds of P. glycyrrhiza just above & right of center (with the distinctly longer leaflets, especially near the base), while the rest are hesperium (all much narrower in outline with short leaflets). The diagnostic short curved hairs along the central stem can be seen in the second photo. The young sori are also typical for this time of year, compared to the other species that have their fresh growth primarily back in the spring rather than fall.
A rather flat & stiff texture for a Licorice Fern, but diagnostic hairs along stem easily seen once dry.

It's not typical to see this species with both fresh and wilted leaves present at the same time, but I'm finding that they can grow fresh fronds at any time of year on occasion. Wilted overwinter fronds, and fresh early-summer growth. Typical soft texture and long pointed leaflets. ID confirmed by short hairs along stem.

This is a follow-up to https://inaturalist.ca/observations/177923380. I appreciate gwenlh's mention of S. elongata, which certainly is recorded in BC but which I hadn't considered. So I specifically looked for examples with noticeably elongated inflorescences. Here is a typical example. It is growing in the open alongside a mid-elevation (850m+) gravel road; main associated plant is Aruncus dioicus, with coniferous forest alongside the road. My aim was to find out if the inflorescence is glandular (S. lepida) or not (S. elongata & the other Solidago spp) as mentioned by stewartwechsler and on https://uwaterloo.ca/astereae-lab/research/goldenrods/classification-and-illustrations/solidago-lepida). I am not sure. Certainly my Olympus TG6 did not pick up these small glands on the petals. The visibly long hairs along the margins of the involucral bracts with glabrous faces that clearly show unfortunately are described for both S. lepida and S. elongata in the Flora of North America.

Plantago macrocarpa-Juncus balticus has a red-listed community on BC CDC (an old record, so recorded as J. arcticus ssp/var balticus). In the Squamish Estuary Juncus balticus is commonly associated with Plantago macrocarpa, but not necessrily as the two dominant species. They grow also with Triglochin maritimum, Carex lyngbyei and Potentilla egedii. In the Cesntral Delta this combination can be seen in a fairly continous line (ends pointing toward Squamish Chief and the yellow gate and bridge at S. end of Chelem Trail.

So far, only one record of T. angustifolia has been recorded in the District of Squamish. This one is too far out in the lake to measure leaf width but it will be worth checking back later this season to visually confirm it's our native species.

I went to look at this site after being told by my colleague @judithofsquamish that she had spotted this non-native species in the Squamish Estuary. I took no measurements - just went by Judith's "bite out of the hot dog" description. These plants were in a small area close to the Corridor Trail at the west side of this wetland, which extends for perhaps 200m. The area has water now, despite the drought, and I haven't tested for depth so I don't know how accessible the area would be for inspection/eradication.

This is a follow-up to gwenlh's interesting find, https://inaturalist.ca/observations/177092756. The leaves of this one example are definitely convex on the outer surface, like T. angustifolia, they are not flat. However, upper and lower portions of the spike both look female, instead the upper being male. Out of the probably >thousand Typha latifolia in this wetland this was the only one I could see that was clearly different and more like T. angustifolia. (The majority are inaccessible owing to all the Rubus bifrons) There are a few that look to have malformed T. latifolia spikes but typical T. latifolia leaves.
